Opportunity for Income Predictor, county, subgroups

Author

JP Walsh

Published

December 20, 2023

Program for the creation of the Opportunity for Income Predictor, subgroups, county level

ACS Code: Initially written by Tina Chelidze and updated by JP Walsh 2022-2023.

Primary data derived from an IPUMS extract for 2021 ACS data (5-year).

Based on processes developed by Paul Johnson and Kevin Werner in SAS.

Create Crosswalk

Prepare the PUMA to county crosswalk. First read in the crosswalk file from the geographic-crosswalks folder.

Code 
puma_county_2021 <- read_csv(here::here("geographic-crosswalks", "data", "geocorr2012_PUMA_Counties_2020.csv"))

Rename variables for working purposes. Add leading zeros to state fips, PUMAs and counties to make them uniform in length.

Code 
puma_county_2021 <- puma_county_2021 %>%
  rename(
    puma = puma12,
    statefip = state) %>%
  mutate(
    statefip = sprintf("%0.2d", as.numeric(statefip)),
    puma = sprintf("%0.5d", as.numeric(puma)),
    county = sprintf("%0.5d", as.numeric(county))
  ) %>% 
  rename_with(tolower)

Break out the county FIP code from the county variable which includes the state FIPs code as the first two digits.

Code 
puma_county_2021 <- puma_county_2021 %>% 
  mutate(county = str_sub(county, -3L, -1L))

Clean for changes in county definitions.

County 019 in state 51 got combined with county 515 among other changes.

Code 
puma_county_2021 <- puma_county_2021 %>% 
  mutate(pop20 = ifelse(statefip == "51" & county == "019", 68676 + 6222, pop20),
         afact = ifelse(statefip == "51" & county == "019", 0.562 + 0.051, afact),
         county = ifelse(statefip == "02" & county == "270", "158", county),
         county = ifelse(statefip == "46" & county == "113", "102", county),
         flag = ifelse(statefip == "51" & county == "515", 1, 0)) %>% 
  filter(flag != 1) %>% 
  select(-flag)

Create quality variable

Add the necessary components to the crosswalk for producing a data quality flag.

Create flags in the PUMA-county crosswalk for counties where a high percentage of the data comes from outside of the county. Per agreed upon guidance, 75% or more from the county is good, below 35% is bad, in between is marginal. This is calculated by taking the product of percentage of PUMA in county and percentage of county in the PUMA for each county-PUMA pairing, and summing across the county.

Create new vars of interest. Products is the sum of the share of the county captured in the PUMA (afact2) and the share of the PUMA captured in the county (afact).

Code 
puma_county <- puma_county_2021 %>%
  mutate(products = afact * afact2)

Calculate the total county population by summing pop20. Pop20 is the population in the PUMA that overlaps with the county - note that GeoCorr presents these numbers so that it already accounts for afact (see What is a Correlation List? on the GeoCorr website https://mcdc.missouri.edu/applications/docs/geocorr-help.html#weightVar).

Code 
puma_county <- puma_county %>%
  group_by(statefip, county) %>%
  mutate(sum_products = sum(products),
         county_pop = sum(pop20)) %>% 
  ungroup()

The average sum of products is 55% (more PUMAs have good quality than less than good). We also want to know particularly small countys, defined by the bottom percentile of population. The table below shows us that the first quartile of county population is 18,962.

Code 
summary(puma_county %>% 
          select(sum_products, county_pop)) 
  sum_products      county_pop      
 Min.   :0.0003   Min.   :      64  
 1st Qu.:0.1391   1st Qu.:   18962  
 Median :0.4814   Median :   68632  
 Mean   :0.5475   Mean   :  571483  
 3rd Qu.:0.9975   3rd Qu.:  523481  
 Max.   :1.0001   Max.   :10014009

Crate an indicator of data quality based on these results. Create an indicator based on sum_product result (1 to 3 with 1 being best). Also create an indicator of small countys (1 is small - define the cutoff as the first quartile calcualted above).

Code 
puma_county <- puma_county %>%
  mutate(
    puma_flag = 
      case_when(
        sum_products >= 0.75 ~ 1,
        sum_products >= 0.35 ~ 2,
        sum_products < 0.35 ~ 3
      ),
    small_county = 
      case_when(
        county_pop >= 18962 ~ 0,
        county_pop < 18962 ~ 1
      )
  )

Save as âpuma_county.csvâ in the intermediate file.

Code 
write_csv(puma_county, here::here("01_financial-well-being", "data", "intermediate", "puma_county.csv"))

Save a version with just the county-level values of data quality variables

Code 
county_puma <- puma_county %>%
  group_by(statefip, county) %>% 
  summarise(puma_flag = mean(puma_flag), 
            small_county = mean(small_county)) %>% 
  ungroup()

Save as âcounty_puma.csvâ in the intermediate file.

Pull microdata

API Pull

Using the API, read in the IPUMS micro data. To check on available surveys you can use the function get_sample_info(âusaâ). This version of the code is currently pulling from â2021câ which is 5-year 2021 ACS data.

Submit the extract. The directory is set to download into the ârawâ data folder inside of the 01_financial-well-being folder. If the data already exists this step will be skipped.

Code 
if(!file.exists(here::here("01_financial-well-being", "data", "raw", "income_5year.dat.gz"))){
  
    usa_ext_umf <-
      define_extract_usa(
        description = "5-year ACS microdata pull for the Opportunity for Income Predictor at the county level, subgroups",
        samples = c("us2021c"),
         variables = list(
      "ADJUST",
      "STATEFIP",
      "PUMA",
      "GQ",
      "HHINCOME",
      "VACANCY",
      "PERNUM",
      "RACE",
      "HISPAN"
    )
      )
    
    usa_ext_umf_submitted <- submit_extract(usa_ext_umf)
    
    usa_ext_complete <- wait_for_extract(usa_ext_umf_submitted)
    
    filepath <-
      download_extract(
        usa_ext_umf_submitted,
        download_dir = here::here("01_financial-well-being", "data", "raw"),
        progress = FALSE
      )
  }

Rename the IPUMS raw files. Filter for .GZ and .XML files in the raw data folder and change the names to income_5year. Note that we filter out files that have income in the name before renaming, this is to prevent changing downloads from the income non-subgroup code.

Code 
if(!file.exists(here::here("01_financial-well-being", "data", "raw", "income_5year.dat.gz"))){
  
    ipums_files <-
      list.files(paste0(here::here("01_financial-well-being", "data", "raw")), full.names = TRUE) %>%
      as_tibble() %>%
      filter(str_detect(value, "dat.gz|xml"), !str_detect(value, "income")) %>%
      pull()
    
    file.rename(ipums_files, c(
      here::here("01_financial-well-being", "data", "raw", "income_5year.dat.gz"),
      here::here("01_financial-well-being", "data", "raw", "income_5year.xml")
    ))
  }

Reformat variable names to lowercase for easier reference throughout the program.

Code 
acs_2021 <- micro_data %>%
  rename_with(tolower)

Drop labels using zap_labels and define variable formats. Household income takes an unknown format upon reading in the raw data, we redefine it as numeric. Provide leading zeros to statefip and PUMA so they match the crosswalk.

Code 
acs_2021 <- acs_2021 %>%
  mutate(
    across(where(is.labelled), ~ zap_labels(.x)),
    hhincome = as.numeric(hhincome),
    statefip = sprintf("%0.2d", as.numeric(statefip)),
    puma = sprintf("%0.5d", as.numeric(puma))
  )

Create race/ethnicity variable.

Code 
acs2021clean <- acs2021clean %>%
  mutate(subgroup = case_when((hispan == 0 & race == 1) ~ 4,
                              (hispan == 0 & race == 2) ~ 1,
                              (hispan == 0 & race %in% 3:9) ~ 3,
                              (hispan %in% 1:4) ~ 2
  ))

Rename the values from number category to race label 4 = âWhite, Non-Hispanicâ 1 = âBlack, Non-Hispanicâ 3 = âOther Races and Ethnicitiesâ 2 = âHispanicâ

Code 
acs2021clean <- acs2021clean %>%
  mutate(subgroup = case_when(subgroup %in% 1 ~ 'Black, Non-Hispanic',
                              subgroup %in% 2 ~ 'Hispanic',
                              subgroup %in% 3 ~ 'Other Races and Ethnicities',
                              subgroup %in% 4 ~ 'White, Non-Hispanic'
  ))

Now have 8,184,425 observations. Run anti_join to see how many cases on the left did not have a match on the right.

Code

Zero. We use all counties.

Drop any observations with NA for afact (i.e.Â there is no county of interest overlapping this PUMA).

Code 
acs2021clean <- acs2021clean %>% 
  filter(!is.na(afact))
Code 
acs2021clean <- acs2021clean %>% 
  filter(afact > 0)

Adjust weight to account for PUMA-to-county mapping (those where unique_types do not equal 1).Drop PUMA flag variable from PUMA_county.

Apply the Adjust variable to household income. Adjust converts the dollar amounts to the amount that they would have been had they been earned entirely during the calendar year. This is to deal with households being surveyed at different times during the year.

Code 
acs2021clean <- acs2021clean %>%
  mutate(hhwt = hhwt*afact, 
         hhincome = hhincome*adjust
  ) %>% 
  select(-puma_flag)

Correct for counties that have been absorbed.

Code 
acs2021clean <- acs2021clean %>% 
  mutate(county = case_when(statefip == "51" & county == "515" ~ "019",
                            statefip == "02" & county == "270" ~ "158",
                            statefip == "46" & county == "113" ~ "102",
                            TRUE ~ county)
  )

Create income metric

Create the income metric (subgroup).

Objective: Calculate the 20th, 50th and 80th percentile of household income for all unique state and county combinations in year 2021.

Aggregation should be weighted by HHWT (this is a household level statistic).

Isolate data to include each household only once (PERNUM == 1 counts head of household only).

Code 
acs2021income <- acs2021clean %>%
  filter(pernum == 1)

Confirm there are no missing values remaining in the data set for the household income variable.

Code 
acs2021income %>%
  filter(is.na(hhincome)) %>% 
  group_by(pernum) %>% 
  count()
# A tibble: 0 x 2
# Groups:   pernum [0]
# i 2 variables: pernum <dbl>, n <int>

Confirm there are no vacant properties included in the data.

Code 
acs2021income %>%
  filter(is.na(vacancy)) %>% 
  group_by(pernum) %>% 
  count()
# A tibble: 0 x 2
# Groups:   pernum [0]
# i 2 variables: pernum <dbl>, n <int>

Calculate quantiles by grouping variable county.

Code 
metrics_income <- acs2021income %>%
  group_by(statefip, county, subgroup) %>%
  summarise(pctl_20 = Hmisc::wtd.quantile(hhincome, weights = hhwt, probs = 0.2), 
                   pctl_50 = Hmisc::wtd.quantile(hhincome, weights = hhwt, probs = 0.5),
                   pctl_80 = Hmisc::wtd.quantile(hhincome, weights = hhwt, probs = 0.8),
                   count = n()) %>% 
  ungroup()

Finish the Data Quality variable

For Income metric: total number of households is the sample size we are checking.

Code 
metrics_income <- metrics_income %>% 
  mutate(size_flag = case_when((count < 30) ~ 1,
                               (count >= 30) ~ 0))

Merge the PUMA flag in & create the final data quality metric based on both size and puma flags

Code 
metrics_income <- left_join(metrics_income, county_puma, by=c("statefip","county"))

Generate the quality variable.

Code 
metrics_income <- metrics_income %>% 
  mutate(pctl_20_quality = case_when(size_flag==0 & puma_flag==1 ~ 1,
                                     size_flag==0 & puma_flag==2 ~ 2,
                                     size_flag==0 & puma_flag==3 ~ 3,
                                     size_flag==1 ~ 3),
         pctl_50_quality = case_when(size_flag==0 & puma_flag==1 ~ 1,
                                     size_flag==0 & puma_flag==2 ~ 2,
                                     size_flag==0 & puma_flag==3 ~ 3,
                                     size_flag==1 ~ 3),
         pctl_80_quality = case_when(size_flag==0 & puma_flag==1 ~ 1,
                                     size_flag==0 & puma_flag==2 ~ 2,
                                     size_flag==0 & puma_flag==3 ~ 3,
                                     size_flag==1 ~ 3),
         subgroup_type = "race-ethnicity"
  )

Keep only relevant variables

Code 
metrics_income <- metrics_income %>% 
  select(statefip, county, subgroup_type, subgroup, pctl_20, pctl_20_quality, 
         pctl_50, pctl_50_quality, pctl_80, 
         pctl_80_quality, size_flag, 
         puma_flag)
